    Leuk Lymphoma. 2020 Dec;61(12):2783-2784.

While TKI are the preferred first-line treatment for chronic phase (CP) CML, 
alloHCT remains an important consideration. The aim is to estimate residual life 
expectancy (RLE) for patients initially diagnosed with CP CML based on timing of 
alloHCT or continuation of TKI in various settings: CP1 CML, CP2 + [after 
transformation to accelerated phase (AP) or blast phase (BP)], AP, or BP. 
Non-transplant cohort included single-institution patients initiating TKI and 
switched TKI due to failure. CIBMTR transplant cohort included CML patients who 
underwent HLA sibling matched (MRD) or unrelated donor (MUD) alloHCT. AlloHCT 
appeared to shorten survival in CP1 CML with overall mortality hazard ratio (HR) 
for alloHCT of 2.4 (95% CI 1.2-4.9; p = .02). In BP CML, there was a trend 
toward higher survival with alloHCT; HR = 0.7 (0.5-1.1; p = .099). AlloHCT in 
CP2 + [HR = 2.0 (0.8-4.9), p = .13] and AP [HR = 1.1 (0.6-2.1); p = .80] is less 
clear and should be determined on a case-by-case basis.

